'''Jordan Pierre Ayew''' (born 11 September 1991) is a Ghanaian professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Winger (association football)|winger]] or [[Forward (association football)|forward]] for {{English football updater|LeicestC}} club [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]]. Born in France, he plays for the [[Ghana national football team|Ghana national team]].

The son of former Ghana national football captain [[Abedi Pele]], and the brother of fellow players [[André Ayew|André]] and [[Ibrahim Ayew]], Ayew began his professional career with [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]], scoring on his senior debut in 2009. After short spells with fellow [[Ligue 1]] clubs [[FC Sochaux-Montbéliard|Sochaux]] and [[FC Lorient|Lorient]], he was signed by English side [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in 2015, finishing his only full season as the team's top scorer as they were relegated from the Premier League; this feat was subsequently repeated with [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] in 2018. Following Swansea's relegation, Ayew was signed by [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]], going on to make over 200 appearances for the club.

Born in France, Ayew made his senior debut for [[Ghana]] in 2010 and has since earned over 110 caps for his country, serving as [[Captain (sports)|captain]] since 2025. He has played for the national team in two [[FIFA World Cup]]s ([[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014]] and [[2022 FIFA World Cup|2022]]), as well as six [[Africa Cup of Nations]] ([[2012 Africa Cup of Nations|2012]], [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations|2015]], [[2017 Africa Cup of Nations|2017]], [[2019 Africa Cup of Nations|2019]], [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations|2021]] and [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations|2023]]), helping them finish runners-up in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |date=10 June 2024 |title=Ghana vs CAR highlights: Jordan Ayew hattrick seal win for Black Stars for 2026 World Cup qualifier |url=https://www.bbc.com/pidgin/articles/c51137j2g7ro |access-date=2024-06-15 |website=BBC News Pidgin}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Marseille===
[[File:OM - FC Porto - Valais Cup 2013 - Jordan Ayew 2.jpg|left|thumb|222x222px|Ayew playing for OM in 2013]]

Ayew joined [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]] as a trainee in 2006. He signed a three-year professional [[Association football contracts|contract]] with Marseille in 2009. Jordan Ayew made his debut for the senior team on 16 December 2009 in a [[Ligue 1|league]] match, scoring the equaliser against [[FC Lorient|Lorient]]. [[Olympique de Marseille|Marseille]] went on to win the match 2–1.<ref>{{LFP|id=ayew-jordan}}</ref>
Ayew scored his second goal against [[OGC Nice|Nice]] at the [[Stade Vélodrome]] on 27 April 2011 in a match which saw his elder brother [[André Ayew]] score a [[Hat-trick#Association football|hat-trick]]. On 1 November 2011, Jordan and André both started a [[UEFA Champions League]] match for the first time against Premier League giants [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]].

On 6 January 2014, he joined Ligue 1 rivals [[FC Sochaux-Montbéliard|Sochaux]] on a loan deal until the end of the [[2013-14 Ligue 1|2013–14 season]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jordan Ayew Officiellement Sochalien|url=http://www.fcsochaux.fr/fr/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5939|publisher=FC Sochaux-Montbéliard|access-date=6 January 2014|date=6 January 2014|archive-date=1 October 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151001142149/http://www.fcsochaux.fr/fr/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=5939|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Lorient===
On 28 July 2014, Ayew signed a four-year contract with [[FC Lorient|Lorient]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Jordan Ayew FC Lorient decision|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/28530377 |work=BBC Sport|access-date=29 July 2014|date=29 July 2014}}</ref> Ayew explained the style and quality of play that Lorient proposed was the reason behind the decision.

===Aston Villa===
On 27 July 2015, Ayew joined [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] on a five-year deal for an undisclosed fee, reported to be in the region of £8&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web|title=Breaking news: Villa sign Ayew |url=http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10265~4891745,00.html |publisher=Aston Villa |access-date=27 July 2015 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151118025652/http://www.avfc.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0%2C%2C10265~4891745%2C00.html |archive-date=18 November 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Aston Villa bid for Lorient's Jordan Ayew accepted, according to Sky sources|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/9922994/aston-villa-bid-for-lorients-jordan-ayew-accepted-according-to-sky-sources|publisher=SkySports|access-date=27 July 2015|date=24 July 2015}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club on 24 October 2015 against his elder brother's club, Swansea City, in the 62nd minute.<ref>{{cite news|title=Aston Villa 1–2 Swansea City|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/football/34558441|work=BBC Sport|access-date=10 November 2015}}</ref> Aston Villa were relegated at the end of the 2015–16 season, winning only 17 points, but Ayew did end the season as their top scorer, albeit with just seven goals.

===Swansea City===
==== 2016–17 season ====
[[File:Jordan Ayew 2017.jpg|thumb|266x266px|Ayew playing for Swansea in 2017]]

On 31 January 2017, Jordan Ayew joined [[Swansea City A.F.C.|Swansea City]] until the end of the 2019–20 season in exchange for Welsh International defender [[Neil Taylor (footballer)|Neil Taylor]], plus a fee from Swansea that can rise to £5&nbsp;million if undisclosed future conditions are met.<ref>{{cite news| title=Jordan Ayew: Swansea sign Aston Villa forward in Neil Taylor swap deal| url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/38800257|work=BBC Sport |date=31 January 2017|access-date=4 February 2017}}</ref> Jordan's elder brother was a Swansea City player during the [[2015–16 Swansea City A.F.C. season|2015–16]] season and later joined him in the winter transfer window of 2018.<ref>{{Cite web | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42767978 | title = Andre Ayew: Swansea City re-sign Ghana forward from West Ham | work = BBC Sport | date = 31 January 2018 | access-date = 2 February 2018 }}</ref> On 12 February 2017, he made his debut in a 2–0 victory over Leicester City after coming on in the 72nd minute for [[Fernando Llorente]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=12 February 2017 |title=Jordan Ayew makes Swansea debut in victory over Leicester - MyJoyOnline.com |url=https://www.myjoyonline.com/jordan-ayew-makes-swansea-debut-in-victory-over-leicester/ |access-date=17 November 2022 |website=My Joy Online }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=15 February 2017 |title=Jordan Ayew: I will repay Swansea City fans |url=https://www.swanseacity.com/news/jordan-ayew-i-will-repay-swansea-city-fans |access-date=18 November 2022 |publisher=Swansea City A.F.C. |language=en}}</ref> In the final match of the season, Ayew scored his debut goal for Swansea by scoring the first goal, an equaliser which led to a their 2–1 comeback victory over [[West Bromwich Albion F.C.|West Bromwich Albion]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Swansea 2–1 West Brom: Fernando Llorente nets late to snatch Swans victory |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/10886884/swansea-2-1-west-brom-fernando-llornente-nets-late-to-snatch-swans-victory |access-date=2022-11-17 |website=Sky Sports |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |title=Swansea City 2–1 West Bromwich Albion |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39912021 |access-date=2022-11-17}}</ref> He played a key role in helping them survive the league and avoid relegation by playing 14 matches, starting nine of those, scoring a goal and assisting three goals.<ref>{{Cite web |date=21 May 2017 |title=Jordan Ayew closes season with first Swansea City goal |url=https://www.goal.com/en-sg/news/jordan-ayew-closes-season-with-first-swansea-city-goal/v84y7buxxi091ld65ewfa5k5h |access-date=18 November 2022 |website=Goal (website)}}</ref>

==== 2017–18 season ====
On 22 August 2017, Ayew put up a man of the match performance by scoring a 20-yard strike goal and assisting another for Tammy Abraham's debut goal in Swansea's EFL Cup match against MK Dons.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Talking Tactics: Jordan Ayew {{!}} Swansea |url=https://www.swanseacity.com/news/talking-tactics-jordan-ayew |access-date=2022-11-18 |publisher=Swansea City A.F.C. |language=en}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite news |title=Milton Keynes Dons 1–4 Swansea City |language=en-GB |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/40932091 |access-date=2022-11-18}}</ref> His goal 20-yard effort was described by news outlet BBC as a tremendous strike.<ref name=":1" /> Ayew scored his first goal in the 2017–18 season, on 26 August 2017, to help The Swans to a 2–0 victory over his future club Crystal Palace.<ref>{{Cite web |date=26 August 2017 |title=Video: Swansea City star Jordan Ayew scores season's first league goal as Swans defeat Crystal Palace |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/swansea-star-jordan-signs-off-for-ghana-duties-with-seasons-first-goal |access-date=2022-11-18 |website=GhanaSoccernet |language=en}}</ref> On 17 January 2018, he scored the opening goal in the Swans' 2–1 FA Cup replay match against Wolverhampton Wanderers.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Pritchard |first=Dafydd |date=17 January 2018 |title=Swansea City 2–1 Wolverhampton Wanderers |work=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/42630627 |access-date=28 November 2022}}</ref>

At the end of his second season, his only full season with the club, he played 44 matches in all competition and scored 11 goals with 7 coming in the league. He finished the season as the club's top goal scorer and was voted the Players' Player of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Gyamera-Antwi |first=Evans |date=3 May 2018 |title=Ayew named Swansea City Player of the Year |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/jordan-ayew-named-swansea-city-player-of-the-year/fzepf6d3ut7k11y8o7hdi6ph4 |access-date=17 November 2022 |website=Goal (website)}}</ref> His solo goal against [[Wolverhampton Wanderers F.C.|Wolverhampton Wanderers]] scored on 17 January 2018 in the FA Cup won the club's goal of the season award.<ref name=":0" /> Despite his performance over the season, Swansea was relegated to the championship. This made it the fourth time he had ended as a club's top goal scorer but the club still getting relegated at the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |date=4 August 2018 |title=The stat that proves Jordan Ayew is the grim reaper of survival hopes |url=https://www.dreamteamfc.com/c/news-gossip/414812/jordan-ayew-relegation-premier-league-stat-swansea-aston-villa/ |access-date=2022-11-18 |website=Dream Team FC |language=en-US}}</ref>{{deprecated inline|certain=y|date=November 2024}}{{better source needed|date=May 2025}}

===Crystal Palace===
==== 2018–19 season ====
On transfer deadline day in August 2018, Ayew joined [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]] on loan for the [[2018–19 Crystal Palace F.C. season|2018–19 season]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/2018/august/jordan-ayew-joins-crystal-palace/|title=Jordan Ayew Joins Crystal Palace|publisher = Crystal Palace F.C.|date=9 August 2018|access-date=9 August 2018}}</ref> He made his debut on 1 September 2018, starting in Palace's 2–0 loss to Southampton. On 15 September, he put on an impressive performance against Huddersfield, providing the assist to [[Wilfried Zaha]]'s goal to earn Palace a 1–0 victory.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=Warlow |first=Robert |date=16 September 2018 |title=Five things we learned as Palace beat Huddersfield |url=https://www.football.london/crystal-palace-fc/fixtures-results/ayew-zaha-palace-talking-points-15157830 |access-date=18 November 2022 |website=Football.London |language=en}}</ref> He was praised for his pressing, hold up play which helped in bringing others into play and allowing the other attackers the opportunity to create chances.<ref name=":2" />

On 2 January 2019, he scored his first league goal for Palace by scoring the opening goal in their 2–0 victory over Wolverhampton Wanderers.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Quao |first=Nathan |date=3 January 2019 |title=Jordan Ayew: Crystal Palace win at Wolves was big |url=https://citinewsroom.com/2019/01/jordan-ayew-crystal-palace-win-at-wolves-was-big/ |access-date=18 November 2022 |website=Citi Newsroom |language=en-US}}</ref> Three days after, Ayew came on in the 68th minute for [[Jaïro Riedewald|Jairo Riedewald]] to score a late winner (in the 86th minute) against [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]] in the FA Cup.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Muro |first=Giuseppe |date=5 January 2019 |title=Crystal Palace 1 Grimsby 0: Jordan Ayew spares Palace blushes late on as they edge past 10-man Town |url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/crystalpalace/crystal-palace-1-grimsby-0-jordan-ayew-spares-palace-blushes-late-on-as-they-edge-past-10man-town-a4031356.html |access-date=18 November 2022 |website=Evening Standard}}</ref>

==== 2019–20 season ====
[[File:Manchester United v Crystal Palace, 5 December 2021 (04).jpg|thumb|206x206px|Ayew (9) playing for Crystal Palace against Manchester United in 2021]]

On 25 July 2019, Ayew made the move permanent with a £2.5m transfer from Swansea City on a three-year deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/2019/july/jordan-ayew-joins-palace-on-three-year-deal/|title=Jordan Ayew joins Palace on three-year deal|publisher=Crystal Palace F.C.|date=25 July 2019|access-date=30 July 2019}}</ref> Ayew scored his first goal of the season on 24 August 2019 against [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] at [[Old Trafford]], netting the opener in the first half against the run of play, latching on to [[Jeffrey Schlupp]]'s flick-on as Crystal Palace secured an historic 2–1 victory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/49378901|title=Crystal Palace manager Roy Hodgson hailed a "heroic victory" after his side stunned Manchester United with an injury-time winner to record their first victory at Old Trafford since 1989.|publisher=BBC|date=24 August 2019|access-date=26 December 2019}}</ref>

On Boxing Day 2019, Ayew scored the match winner in stoppage time as Crystal Palace came from behind to defeat [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] 2–1.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2019/dec/26/crystal-palace-west-ham-united-premier-league-match-report|title=Jordan Ayew's last-minute solo goal sees Crystal Palace sink West Ham|website=The Guardian|date=26 December 2019|access-date=26 December 2019}}</ref> It was Ayew's 21st goal in the Premier League with 20 having been scored in the second half (95%) – the highest such ratio of any player with 20+ goals in the competition's history.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.goal.com/en-us/news/jordan-ayew-makes-bold-statement-about-sensational-solo/109mt20qn56kw1m2sv2xtk0ocq|title=Jordan Ayew makes bold statement with sensational solo strike against West Ham|website=Goal (website)|date=26 December 2019|access-date=26 December 2019}}</ref> On 20 June 2020, he scored to assist the Eagles defeat Bournemouth 2–0, making him the highest-scoring Ghanaian in Premier League history with 25 goals. He surpassed [[Tony Yeboah]] who scored 24 goals while playing for [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Teye |first=Prince Narkortu |date=21 June 2020 |title=Jordan Ayew pulls away from Tony Yeboah as Ghana's top Premier League scorer |url=https://www.goal.com/news/jordan-ayew-pulls-away-from-tony-yeboah-as-ghanas-top-premier-league-scorer/1xebh6yqi5s4h123p6sc9ppzzs |access-date=2 March 2024 |website=Goal (website) }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Dove |first=Ed |date=23 June 2020 |title=Ranking Jordan Ayew, Tony Yeboah & Ghana's greatest Prem goalscorers |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/lists/ranking-jordan-ayew-tony-yeboah--ghanas-greatest-prem-goalscorers/58gof3tv35fm1660y7hfpb6gu |access-date=2 March 2024 |website=Goal (website) }}</ref>

At the end of the season, Ayew was the highest goalscorer for Crystal Palace with 9 goals, and won the [[Crystal Palace F.C. Player of the Year|Crystal Palace Player of the season]], Players' Player of the season and Goal of the season awards.<ref>{{Cite web|date=28 July 2020|title=Ayew recognised for impressive Crystal Palace season with three awards|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/sport/football/crystal-palace-jordan-ayew-player-of-the-season-awards-a4511041.html|access-date=2 August 2020|website=Evening Standard|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Crystal Palace 2019–20 Premier League Player Stats – Goals |url=https://www.premierleague.com/stats/top/players/goals?se=274&cl=6 |access-date=2 August 2020 |publisher=Premier League |archive-date=7 February 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230207192821/https://www.premierleague.com/stats/top/players/goals?se=274&cl=6 |url-status=dead }}</ref>

==== 2020–2023 ====
In the 2020–21 season, Ayew scored his only goal in the season in a 4–1 victory over Leeds United.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Grounds |first=Ben |date=8 November 2020 |title=Crystal Palace 4–1 Leeds United: Ebere Eze inspires Eagles to fine victory |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/12126309/crystal-palace-4-1-leeds-united-ebere-eze-inspires-eagles-to-fine-victory |access-date=2 March 2024 |website=Sky Sports |language=en}}</ref> He subsequently went 43 games without a goal before scoring a 65th-minute equaliser to secure a 2–2 Premier League draw for Crystal Palace against Southampton on 16 December 2021.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Marsh |first=Charlotte |date=16 December 2021 |title=Crystal Palace 2–2 Southampton: Jordan Ayew scores first Premier League goal in 43 games to rescue draw for Eagles |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/12495217/crystal-palace-2-2-southampton-jordan-ayew-scores-first-premier-league-goal-in-43-games-to-rescue-draw-for-eagles |access-date=2 March 2024 |website=Sky Sports }}</ref> On 4 April 2022, he scored the second goal in a 3–0 home victory over Arsenal at [[Selhurst Park]].<ref>{{Cite web |last=Jones |first=Lewis |date=5 April 2022 |title=Crystal Palace 3–0 Arsenal: Gunners left in the wake of perfect Palace as top-four race hots up |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11661/12579713/crystal-palace-3-0-arsenal-gunners-left-in-the-wake-of-perfect-palace-as-top-four-race-hots-up |access-date=2 March 2024 |website=Sky Sports }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Mabuka |first=Dennis |date=5 April 2022 |title=Ghana's Jordan Ayew 'proved people wrong' with left foot for Crystal Palace against Arsenal |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/ghana-jordan-ayew-proved-people-wrong-crystal-palace-arsenal/bltff7536368e1c750e |access-date=2 March 2024 |website=Goal (website) }}</ref> At the end of the [[2021–22 Crystal Palace F.C. season|2021–22 season]], he was played 31 league matches, scored 3 goals and made 3 assists.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Jordan Ayew 2021–22 Premier League Stats |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/5595/player/stats?co=1&se=418 |access-date=2 March 2024 |publisher=Premier League}}</ref>

In June 2022, he signed a contract extension keeping him at the club until 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |date=8 June 2022 |title=Palace confirm contract extensions with four senior first-team players – News |url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/announcement/jordan-ayew-nathaniel-clyne-james-mcarthur-and-james-tomkins-sign-crystal-palace-extensions/2022-06-08/ |access-date=9 June 2022 |publisher=Crystal Palace F.C. |language=en-GB}}</ref> Ayew scored his first goal of the 2022–23 season and his first goal after his contract extension on New Year's Eve, ending his goal drought failing to score from 13 starts in 15 matches. He scored the opening goal to help Crystal Palace to 2–0 victory over Bournemouth.<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 January 2023 |title=Bournemouth 0–2 Crystal Palace: Jordan Ayew and Eberechi Eze give visitors deserved win at Vitality Stadium |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/26806/12777366/bournemouth-0-2-crystal-palace-jordan-ayew-and-eberechi-eze-give-visitors-deserved-win-at-vitality-stadium |access-date=2 March 2024 |website=Sky Sports }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |date=31 December 2023 |title=Ayew scores first goal of the season as Eze, Olise sparkle for Crystal Palace in win over Bournemouth |url=https://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/jordan-ayew-finally-ends-goal-drought-in-crystal-palace-win-over-bournemouth/bltea3d728a6263a4b9 |access-date=2 March 2024 |website=Goal (website) }}</ref> On 9 April 2023, he scored a brace inspiring Crystal Palace to an emphatic 5–1 away victory against Leeds United.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Taylor |first=Louise |date=9 April 2023 |title=Jordan Ayew's double inspires Crystal Palace to emphatic victory at Leeds |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2023/apr/09/leeds-crystal-palace-premier-league-match-report |access-date=2 March 2024 |work=The Guardian |language=en-GB |issn=0261-3077}}</ref> At the end of the [[2022–23 Crystal Palace F.C. season|2022–23 season]], Ayew played in all 38 league matches scoring four goals and providing three assists.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Jordan Ayew 2022–23 Premier League Stats |url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/5595/player/stats?co=1&se=489 |access-date=2 March 2024 |publisher=Premier League}}</ref>

==== 2023–24 season ====
On 1 November 2023, Ayew signed a contract extension until 2025.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/announcement/jordan-ayew-contract-extension-2025/|title=Jordan Ayew signs extension until 2025|publisher=Crystal Palace F.C.|date=1 November 2023|accessdate=6 November 2023}}</ref> On 27 February 2024, he made his 200th Crystal Palace appearance in all competitions, marking the milestone with a player of the match-winning performance including scoring one goal and assisting another in a 3–0 victory over Burnley.<ref>{{Cite web |date=27 February 2024 |title=Jordan Ayew celebrates 200 Palace appearances |url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/club/jordan-ayew-crystal-palace-200-appearances/ |access-date=1 March 2024 |publisher=Crystal Palace F.C. }}</ref> Days after that, he was adjudged the Crystal Palace men's Player of the Month for February.<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 March 2024 |title=Ayew voted February's cinch Player of the Month – News |url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/announcement/jordan-ayew-cinch-player-of-the-month-winner-february-2024/ |access-date=2 March 2024 |publisher=Crystal Palace F.C. }}</ref>

===Leicester City===
On 23 August 2024, Leicester City signed Ayew on a two-year contract worth £5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/ced1544jjqdo |title=Leicester sign Palace winger Ayew for £5m |date=23 August 2024 |access-date=23 August 2024 }}</ref> He made his debut for the club on 24 August in a 2–1 defeat to [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]], coming on for [[Bobby Decordova-Reid|Bobby De Cordova-Reid]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Jordan Ayew makes Leicester City debut in loss to Fulham |date=24 August 2024 |url=https://citisportsonline.com/2024/08/epl-on-citi-jordan-ayew-makes-leicester-city-debut-in-loss-to-fulham/}}</ref> He scored his first goal for the club in a 4–0 win against [[Tranmere Rovers F.C.|Tranmere Rovers]] in the [[2024–25 EFL Cup|EFL Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Leicester Beat Tranmere To Advance In Carabao Cup |url=https://www.lcfc.com/news/4098173/leicester-beat-tranmere-to-advance-in-carabao-cup/featured?lang=en |website=lcfc.com |access-date=29 August 2024}}</ref> On 19 October, he tallied his first league goal for the club when he scored a stoppage time winner against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/cd98w3815d5t |title=Southampton vs Leicester City |work=BBC Sport |author=Phil McNulty |date=19 October 2024 |access-date=19 October 2024 }}</ref> Leicester City endured successive relegation campaigns that saw them drop from the Premier League to the [[EFL Championship]] and then further into [[EFL League One]], taking his total career relegations to six across five clubs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pulse.com.gh/story/jordan-ayew-six-relegations-5-clubs-whats-next-for-the-black-stars-captain-2026042710473663510 |title=Jordan Ayew: Six relegations, 5 clubs – What’s next for the Black Stars captain? |publisher=Pulse Ghana |date=27 April 2026 }}</ref>

On 24 May 2026, the club announced it was releasing the player following relegation.<ref>{{Cite web |date=2026-05-24 |title=Leicester City: Jordan Ayew and Ricardo Pereira among 10 players leaving |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/cp8p4ydl5z8o |access-date=2026-05-24 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

==International career==
[[File:Jordan Ayew Mali vs Ghana (cropped).jpg|left|thumb|236x236px|Ayew playing for Ghana in 2015]]

Born in France, Ayew is of Ghanaian and Lebanese descent and holds dual Ghanaian and French citizenship.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Jordan AYEW |url=https://www.unfp.org/joueur/jordan-ayew-16294/ |access-date=2023-07-21 |website=unfp.org}}</ref> He made his first senior [[Cap (sport)|appearance]] for [[Ghana national football team|Ghana]] on 5 September 2010, in a 3–0 [[2012 & 2013 Africa Cup of Nations qualification|2012 AFCON Qualification]] match win against Swaziland, at the [[Somhlolo National Stadium]] in [[Lobamba]], Swaziland.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghana beats Swaziland 3–0 in 2012 qualifier|url=http://www.ghanafa.org/blackstars/201009/5034.php|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100908090524/http://www.ghanafa.org/blackstars/201009/5034.php|url-status=dead|archive-date=8 September 2010|publisher=[[Ghana Football Association]]|access-date=7 June 2012|date=5 September 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Olympique de Marseille's Jordan Ayew Yearns For More With Ghana|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/89/africa/2010/09/07/2105589/olympique-de-marseilles-jordan-ayew-yearns-for-more-with |author=K.N.S Mensah|work=Goal (website)|access-date=7 June 2012|date=7 September 2010}}</ref> On 1 June 2012, Ayew scored his first and second international [[Goal (sport)|goals]] in a [[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)#Group D|2014 World Cup qualification]] match win against [[Lesotho national football team|Lesotho]], at the [[Kumasi Sports Stadium]] in [[Kumasi]], Ghana.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ghana 7–0 Lesotho (2014 FIFA World Cup Qualifiers)|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/africa/matches/round=258334/match=300176007/index.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528073114/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/preliminaries/africa/matches/round=258334/match=300176007/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=28 May 2012|publisher=[[FIFA|Fédération Internationale de Football Association]] (FIFA)|access-date=7 June 2012|date=1 June 2012}}</ref> In December 2011, Ayew was named to the Ghana national team provisional 25-man squad for the [[2012 Africa Cup of Nations]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1658/ghana/2011/12/15/2804053/ghana-announce-25-man-squad-for-2012-africa-cup-of-nations|title=Ghana announce 25-man squad for 2012 Africa Cup of Nations|last=Mensah|first=Kent|access-date=7 June 2012|date=15 December 2011|work=Goal (website)}}</ref> and in January 2012 he was selected for the tournament's 23-man squad.<ref name="Jordan Ayew - 2012 Africa Cup of Nations profile">{{cite web|url=http://www.mtnfootball.com/africa/african-tournaments/african-cup-of-nations/2012-player-profiles/ghana/jordan-ayew.html|title=Jordan Ayew – 2012 Africa Cup of Nations profile|access-date=7 June 2012|work=mtnfootball.com|publisher=[[MTN Group]]|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131007123731/http://www.mtnfootball.com/africa/african-tournaments/african-cup-of-nations/2012-player-profiles/ghana/jordan-ayew.html|archive-date=7 October 2013}}</ref>

In June 2014, he was included in the Ghanaian squad for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]]. In Ghana's last warm-up match before the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] in Brazil on 9 June 2014, Ayew came on as a first-half substitute for the injured [[Majeed Waris]] and ended up scoring a hat-trick in a 4–0 victory over [[South Korea national football team|South Korea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/fifa-world-cup/story/1863563/ghana-4-0-south-korea-ayew-hat-trick |title=Ghana wins final World Cup warmup |publisher=ESPNFC |date=9 June 2014 |access-date=9 June 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gh/news/4389/ghana/2014/06/10/4871892/ghana-4-0-south-korea-j-ayews-hat-trick-inspires-confidence?ICID=HP_BN_1|title=Ghana 4–0 South Korea: J. Ayew's hat-trick inspires confidence ahead of World Cup|last=Mensah|first=Kent|access-date=9 June 2014|date=10 June 2014|work=Goal (website)}}</ref>

Jordan Ayew was part of the [[Ghana national football team|Ghanaian]] team in [[2015 Africa Cup of Nations]] which took place in [[Equatorial Guinea]] that took a silver medal as result of losing out to [[Ivory Coast national football team|Ivory Coast]] on a [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]] whom they clinch the [[Africa Cup of Nations|African Cup]], which occurred on 8 February 2015.

[[File:Ghana-Gabon (4).jpg|thumb|250x250px|Ayew (left) playing for Ghana at the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]]]]
He was part of the Ghanaian team in the [[2021 Africa Cup of Nations]] that was eliminated at the group stage of the competition.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Jordan Ayew joins up with Ghana squad for Afcon 2021 – News|url=https://www.cpfc.co.uk/news/first-team/jordan-ayew-named-in-ghana-squad-for-africa-cup-of-nations-2022/2022-01-04/|access-date=26 January 2022|publisher=Crystal Palace F.C.|date=4 January 2022 |language=en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|date=18 January 2022|title='We weren't good enough' – Jordan Ayew admits after AFCON 2021 exit|url=https://citisportsonline.com/2022/01/18/we-werent-good-enough-jordan-ayew-admits-after-afcon-2021-exit/|access-date=26 January 2022|website=Citi Sports Online|language=en-US}}</ref> In January 2024, he was named in the 27-man squad for the [[2023 Africa Cup of Nations]] in Ivory Coast.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ghanafa.org/chris-names-squad-for-africa-cup-of-nations-cote-divoire-2023|title=Chris Hughton names squad for Africa Cup of Nations Cote D'Ivoire 2023|publisher=Ghana Football Association|date=1 January 2024|access-date=3 January 2024}}</ref> He scored two penalties in his 100th international cap, which ended in a 2–2 draw against [[Mozambique national football team|Mozambique]] in the last group stage match of the African competition.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/67977897 |title=Mozambique 2–2 Ghana |work=BBC Sport |date=22 January 2024 }}</ref>

He featured and scored in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup qualification (CAF)|2026 World Cup qualifiers]] match on 6 June 2024 in which Ghana beat [[Mali national football team|Mali]] 2–1,<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 June 2024 |title=Mali 1–2 Ghana player ratings: Partey leads from the front as Jordan supplies the fire power – MyJoyOnline |url=https://www.myjoyonline.com/mali-1-2-ghana-player-ratings-partey-leads-from-the-front-as-jordan-supplies-the-fire-power/ |access-date=2024-06-11 |website=myjoyonline.com |language=en-US}}</ref> he also scored a [[hat-trick]] when the Black Stars beat the [[Central African Republic national football team|Central African Republic]] on 10 June 2024 at the [[Baba Yara Stadium]] in Kumasi.<ref>{{Cite news |last=GhanaSoccerNet |date=10 June 2024 |title=Ghana 4–3 Central African Republic – Black Stars player ratings from 2026 World Cup qualifier |url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/ghana-4-3-central-african-republic-black-stars-player-ratings-from-2026-world-cup-qualifier}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Godfred |first=Yaw |title=Jordan Ayew's hat-trick hands Ghana 4–3 victory over Central African Republic – NSEM |url=https://nsem.com.gh/118175/, |access-date=2024-06-12 |website=Jordan Ayew's hat-trick hands Ghana 4–3 victory over Central African Republic – NSEM }}{{Dead link|date=August 2025 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In November 2024, Ghana coach [[Otto Addo]] name Jordan Ayew captain of the team ahead of crucial [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations qualification|Afcon 2025 qualification]] matches.<ref>{{Cite web |date=7 November 2024 |title=Jordan Ayew to captain Black Stars against Niger and Angola in AFCON 2025 Qualifier – Radio Univers 105.7fm |url=https://univers.ug.edu.gh/jordan-ayew-to-captain-black-stars-against-niger-and-angola-in-afcon-2025-qualifier/ |access-date=2024-11-15 |language=en-US}}</ref>

On 2 June 2026, he was named in the 26-man squad for the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ghanafa.org/carlos-queiroz-names-2026-fifa-world-cup-squad |title=Carlos Queiroz names 2026 FIFA World Cup squad |publisher=[[Ghana Football Association]] |date=June 2, 2026 |access-date=June 2, 2026 |archive-date=June 2, 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260602044349/https://www.ghanafa.org/carlos-queiroz-names-2026-fifa-world-cup-squad |url-status=live }}</ref> On the same day, he featured in his 120th international match in a 1–1 friendly draw with [[Wales national football team|Wales]], equaling the record for the most international appearances by a Ghanaian player, previously set by his brother [[André Ayew]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/articles/c1k2xlngdk7o |title=Fifa World Cup 2026: What you need to know about Ghana |publisher=BBC Sport |date=5 June 2026 }}</ref>

==Personal life==
Ayew is the son of Maha Ayew and [[Abedi Pele]]. His maternal grandfather, Alhaji A.A. Khadir,<ref>{{Cite web|date=4 February 2016|title=Andre, Jordan Ayew lose grandfather|url=https://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/SportsArchive/Andre-Jordan-Ayew-lose-grandfather-412878|access-date=30 September 2021|website=GhanaWeb|language=en}}</ref> is [[Lebanese people|Lebanese]].<ref>{{Cite web|date=4 February 2016|title=Ghana stars Andre, Jordan Ayew lose grandfather|url=https://ghanasoccernet.com/ghana-stars-andre-jordan-ayew-lose-grand-father|access-date=20 July 2021|website=GhanaSoccernet|language=en}}</ref> His father, uncles [[Kwame Ayew|Kwame]] and Sola, and brothers [[André Ayew|André]] and [[Ibrahim Ayew|Ibrahim]] are all current or former professional footballers as well as a sister, Imani. Ayew is a practising [[Muslim]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Picture: Jordan & Andre Ayew pictured in Muslim prayers|url=http://ghanasoccernet.com/picture-jordan-andre-ayew-pictured-in-muslim-prayers/|publisher=ghanasoccernet.com|date=21 December 2013|access-date=4 April 2014}}</ref> He has never been married but shares two children with Denise Acquah and another older son from a previous relationship.

